  "answer": "**Slokantara, Chapter 1.**\n\nThe verse is:\n\n> *Even a stranger, if helpful, is a kinsman; even a kinsman, if harmful, is a stranger.*  \n> *A disease born of the body is harmful; a forest herb that helps is a friend.*[^1]\n\nThe named exemplum in the commentary immediately follows:\n\n> Who is seen to be like this? It is Sugrīva. He was pained by his kinsman, named Bāli. But Rāma and Lakṣmaṇa, though they were strangers, were nevertheless sought by him in the middle of the forest to be the medicine for Sugrīva's pain.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Slokantara, *Chapter 1*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-slokantara-d7a628/01/translation/#p-bf093b).\n[^2]: Slokantara, *Chapter 1*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-slokantara-d7a628/01/translation/#p-1c880b).",
